node.text: Videos showing people smuggling migrants past Border Patrol checkpoints and flashing thousands of dollars in cash are being posted on TikTok, Texas State Troopers say. This is a new and dangerous tactic to recruit teens to drive migrants from the US-Mexico border to Houston and other Texas cities — with one video offering $4,500 per person they smuggle. CNN's @rosaflorescnn reports.

node.title: Mexican cartels are recruiting teens on TikTok to smuggle migrants

node.text:
The US Food and Drug Administration on Monday granted full approval to the Pfizer/BioNTech Covid-19 vaccine for people age 16 and older. This is the first coronavirus vaccine approved by the FDA, and is expected to open the door to more vaccine mandates. The Pfizer/BioNTech vaccine has been authorized for emergency use in the United States since mid-December for people age 16 and older. In May, the authorization was extended to those 12 and older. Out of more than 170 million people in the United States fully vaccinated against Covid-19, more than 92 million have received the Pfizer/BioNTech vaccine.

📸: Robyn Beck/AFP/Getty Images

All these illustrations were made using a ballpoint pen. Yes, that’s thousands of tiny lines made by a simple ballpoint pen. Nigerian artist Jacqueline Suowari said it takes months of drawing meticulous layers to complete these works – some up to eight feet tall.

"I like to look at each stroke as the human experience. One experience, one stroke – and the gathering, and layering, and falling together of all the strokes creates the person and their character,” Suowari said. 

(📸: Retro Africa Gallery/Jacqueline Suowari)

node.text:
Researchers found the fossils of three new species of early mammals in Wyoming, according to a study published Wednesday in the Journal of Systematic Palaeontology. These creatures are believed to have lived alongside the dinosaurs about 66 million years ago and thrived after they went extinct. ⁠
⁠
The newly discovered mammals – shown in the illustration above (left to right) – are Conacodon hettingeri, Miniconus jeanninae and Beornus honeyi.⁠
⁠
(📸: Banana Art Studio)

node.text:
The artist behind the world's first underwater sculpture park unveiled his latest sub-aquatic project: The Museum of Underwater Sculpture in Cyprus. It costs $1.1 million to make and is made up of 93 sculptures by Jason deCaires Taylor. The museum explores the relationship between man and nature.

"I tried to incorporate as many references to climate change and habitat loss and pollution as I could, because those are really the defining issues of our era," Taylor told CNN.

(📸: MUSAN/Costas Constantinou/@jasondecairestaylor)
